[DhtmlXQ_comment0]mm xqjwms sw 01010402 One Elephant Down||||Question: Black first. Can Black attempt a draw?[/DhtmlXQ_comment0]
[DhtmlXQ_comment1]Preparing the horse for an exchange is a very important move to aim for a draw.[/DhtmlXQ_comment1]
[DhtmlXQ_comment18]And black would have successfully simplified the endgame to that of red's 1r1p2a2e vs black's 1r1h2a1e, which would be a draw.||Conclusion:||From the above 2 examples, it can be seen that when you are two elephants down, the following must be taken note off:||a) you must exploit your opponent's weaknesses and maneuver your material correctly for attack, such that you would be aiming for a winning situation or material gain(s).||b) if the attack you mount is unable to really threaten the opponent, you should try to simplify the game by exchanging the opponent's main attacking pieces or other pieces assisting in the attack. This is done to try to simplify the game so that it becomes impossible for your opponent to win.||c) when you are down an elephant, NEVER give your opponent's CANNON a chance to live up to its potential.[/DhtmlXQ_comment18]
